Build a production-grade local web application: a Kubernetes/OpenShift Log Explorer designed for stable debugging, not real-time streaming.

This is a strict full-stack specification (backend + frontend + UX + data flow). No improvisation allowed.

---

🎯 CORE PRODUCT GOAL

A developer tool that:

- Provides deterministic log viewing per single pod
- Uses snapshot + refresh model (NO live streaming)
- Has clean UX (Kibana-like inspection, VSCode-like speed)
- Never loses context or scroll position
- Clearly separates "existing logs" vs "new logs"

---

🧭 CRITICAL DATA DISCOVERY FLOW (MANDATORY ORDER)

The entire system MUST follow this hierarchy:

STEP 1 — PROJECTS (Namespaces)

Backend call:

oc get projects -o json

Frontend:

- Searchable dropdown (typeahead)
- Select ONE project only

---

STEP 2 — DEPLOYMENTS (filtered by project)

Backend call:

oc get deployments -n <project> -o json

Frontend:

- Searchable dropdown
- Must be filtered by selected project

---

STEP 3 — PODS (filtered by deployment)

Backend call:

oc get pods -n <project> -o json

Frontend:

- Filter pods by deployment label selector
- Searchable dropdown
- Must allow selection of ONE pod only

---

🚨 CRITICAL RULE

- ONLY ONE POD ACTIVE
- Switching pod MUST:
  - clear logs immediately
  - reset state
  - reset numbering
  - cancel pending refresh

---

🧱 BACKEND DESIGN (STRICT)

Backend is a thin wrapper over "oc" only

Endpoints:

1. Projects

- "GET /projects"
- wraps "oc get projects"

2. Deployments

- "GET /deployments?project=..."
- wraps "oc get deployments -n ..."

3. Pods

- "GET /pods?project=..."
- wraps "oc get pods -n ..."

4. Logs (initial)

GET /logs?pod=...&project=...&tail=N

wraps:

oc logs <pod> -n <project> --tail=N

5. Logs refresh

GET /logs/refresh?pod=...&since=<timestamp>

wraps:

oc logs <pod> -n <project> --since-time=<timestamp>

